Data Science Pipeline Tutorial¶

Lucas Balangero CMSC320 Final Project Tutorial 5/17/2021

Introduction¶

In This tutorial, I will be showing how to do a data science analysis on motorcycle accidents compared to car accidents using Python. I have recently decided to start riding a motorcycle and wanted to know how much more dangerous motorcycles are compared to car.

Set Up¶

Here are are all the imports I will be using for this project. Pandas will be used for Data fraames, matplotlib for plots, and sklearn for linear regression lines. Line 6-7 resize the graph so they are easier to see.

Data Loading¶

I will be loading a data from https://opendata.maryland.gov/ which is an open source website from the U.S. Government. Since I will be riding mostly in Maryland, thats where I will like to focus on. The 1.24 million events recorded are from 2015 to 2020. The exact link for this database is https://opendata.maryland.gov/Public-Safety/Maryland-Statewide-Vehicle-Crashes-Vehicle-Details/mhft-5t5y

Since I will be looking at both cars and motorcycles, I will be creating two subsets for both motorcycles and cars.

Data Visualization¶

Next, it is important that the data can be visualized, and one way to do this is with graphs. In the bottom graph, I have created a graph showing the frequency of crashes that happend at different events, separated if there was another vehicle involved or not.

In [8]:
#tallies number of accidents that happend at each type of movement to see what is most frequent
motor_other_vehicle = motorcycles[motorcycles['HARM_EVENT_DESC'] == "Other Vehicle"]
motor_own_fault = motorcycles[motorcycles['HARM_EVENT_DESC'] != "Other Vehicle"]

#create Series of Motorcylists faults and other vehicles faults
movement_t_ov = motor_other_vehicle['MOVEMENT_DESC'].value_counts()
movement_t_of = motor_own_fault['MOVEMENT_DESC'].value_counts()

#Create Conjoin series
movement_types_motor_cat = pd.concat([movement_t_ov,movement_t_of], axis=1)
movement_types_motor_cat.columns = ["Other Vehicle", "Own Fault"]

movement_types_motorcycles_bar = movement_types_motor_cat.plot.bar(xlabel = "Movement Type",
                                                                   ylabel = "Total Accidents",
                                                                   stacked=True,
                                                                   title = "Total Motorcycle Crashes based on Movement Type From 2015-2020")

Another thing we can look at is the frequency of different damage levels of vehicles after the crash in motorcycle crashes compared to passenger cars.

While the majority of crashes recorded are disabling for both cars and motorcycles, it looks like the percentage of disabled crashes in a motorcycle isn't as high at in cars. One slight problem with this data that I noticed is that majority of vehicle crashes could be with little or no damage to the vehicle. However, these small crashes would not be recorded as frequent as in bigger colision which is why I think there is a large amount of disabled vehicles.

Another way we can visualize our data is with a heat map. I am using the libarary called seaborn to help create a heatmap to find any correlations between columns in our dataset. Something that I would be interested in looking for here is correlations with BODY_TYPE_CODE which tells us what type of vehicle was reported in the crash.

In [44]:
#combining both datasets of motorcycles and cars
df = pd.concat([data[data["BODY_TYPE_DESC"] == "Motorcycle"], data[data["BODY_TYPE_DESC"] == "Passenger Car"]])
df =df[df["HARM_EVENT_DESC"] != "Off Road"]

plt.subplots(figsize = (16,11))
g = sns.heatmap(df.corr("spearman"), annot = True, cmap = "YlGnBu", linewidths=.5)
g.set_title("Correlation Matrix between Columns")

Two values that stood out to me that could be worthwhile to look at are MOVEMENT_CODE (tells what type of movement the vehichle was in, Ex: Parked, accelerating, turning, etc), SPEED_LIMIT (tells use what the speed limit was for the road they were in), HARM_EVENT_CODE (tells use who or what was involved in the crash), and DAMAGE_CODE (tells how bad the crash was). Theres seems to be some sort of correlation between these values and BODY_TYPE_CODE.

Machine Learning¶

From here, our next step is to implement some machine learning to be able to find stronger correlations between this data and see if a linear regression model fits the data. This would help us find what the differences are in car crashes as oppose to motorcycle crashes, and how likely someone is to get in a severe crash.

Next we have to create the x and y values to train the dataset before building a linear regression model.

Create Linear Regression Model:

In [85]:
model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model.fit(x_train, y_train)

co = model.coef_
inter = model.intercept_

y_test_pred = model.predict(x_test)
y_train_pred = model.predict(x_train)

accuracy_train = model.score(x_train, y_train)
accuracy_test = model.score(x_test, y_test)

print(f"Coefficient: {co}")
print(f"Interception: {inter}")
print(f"Y Test Prediction: {y_test_pred}")
print(f"Y Train Prediction: {y_train_pred}")
print(f"Accuracy Train: {accuracy_train}")
print(f"Accuracy Test: {accuracy_test}")

rc = RobustScaler()
motorcycles2[columns] = rc.fit_transform(motorcycles2[columns])

y = motorcycles2['DAMAGE_CODE']
x = motorcycles2.drop('DAMAGE_CODE', axis = 1)

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x,y, test_size = .2, random_state = 12)
print(x_train.shape, x_test.shape)

motor_model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
motor_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

co = motor_model.coef_
inter = motor_model.intercept_

y_test_pred = motor_model.predict(x_test)
y_train_pred = motor_model.predict(x_train)

accuracy_train = motor_model.score(x_train, y_train)
accuracy_test = motor_model.score(x_test, y_test)
